abstract: High doses of vitamin E may help people with Alzheimer’s disease maintain the ability to perform routine daily tasks, a new study finds, even though it does not slow cognitive decline.
snippet: High doses of vitamin E may help people with Alzheimer’s disease maintain the ability to perform routine daily tasks, a new study finds, even though it does not slow cognitive decline.
lead_paragraph: Updated, 6:17 p.m. |
headline.main: Vitamin E Slows Decline of Some Alzheimer’s Patients in Study

abstract: Alzheimer’s disease is scary, but that’s no reason to waste money on a test that really doesn’t help.
snippet: Alzheimer’s disease is scary, but that’s no reason to waste money on a test that really doesn’t help.
lead_paragraph: PHILADELPHIA — ALMOST every day I worry about whether my parents have Alzheimer’s. My dad is 86 and my mother is about to turn 80. Just because of their age they are at high risk for the disease, and I constantly wonder if their forgetfulness is “normal” or a sign of the worst.

abstract: A man suffering from Alzheimer’s somehow ended up miles from home, jiggling a couple’s doorknob in the pre-dawn hours, and his shooting death has added another chapter to the debate over self-defense laws.
snippet: A man suffering from Alzheimer’s somehow ended up miles from home, jiggling a couple’s doorknob in the pre-dawn hours, and his shooting death has added another chapter to the debate over self-defense laws.
lead_paragraph: CHICKAMAUGA, Ga. — Deanne Westbrook had tried everything to keep her husband, Ronald, in the house.

abstract: People who have terminal diseases are living longer. Experts say simple strategies can make the most of the money at hand for those with foresight.
snippet: People who have terminal diseases are living longer. Experts say simple strategies can make the most of the money at hand for those with foresight.
lead_paragraph: PATRICK SKELDON, a commercial airline pilot, started having trouble walking in the autumn of 2003. His doctor thought he had a vitamin deficiency and prescribed supplements. When those didn’t work, the doctor referred him to a neurologist. The next year, he was told he had amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, more commonly known as Lou Gehrig’s disease. He was 59.

headline.main: Advice About Assisted Living for Aging Relatives, Part 2

abstract: Debra Drelich, a specialist in geriatric care,  answers questions about the types of facilities for assisted living, age guidelines, licensure  and “aging gracefully in place.”
snippet: Debra Drelich, a specialist in geriatric care,  answers questions about the types of facilities for assisted living, age guidelines, licensure  and “aging gracefully in place.”
lead_paragraph: Readers have sent more than 100  questions and suggestions to Debra Drelich, a specialist in geriatric care, about assisted living and other special living arrangements for aging relatives.

abstract: The $33.2 million grant will help finance a clinical trial to test a treatment on people 60 to 75 who have no symptoms of the disease, but do have two copies of a gene known to greatly increase the risk of getting it.
snippet: The $33.2 million grant will help finance a clinical trial to test a treatment on people 60 to 75 who have no symptoms of the disease, but do have two copies of a gene known to greatly increase the risk of getting it.
lead_paragraph: In the most significant sign yet of a broad shift in the focus of Alzheimer’s research from treating to preventing the disease, the federal government announced on Wednesday its largest grant so far to test an Alzheimer’s drug on healthy people at greatest risk for the most common form of the disease.

abstract: Recent developments in health and science news. This week: A molasses spill has been killing marine life and a $33.2 million grant will go toward Alzheimer’s research.
snippet: Recent developments in health and science news. This week: A molasses spill has been killing marine life and a $33.2 million grant will go toward Alzheimer’s research.
lead_paragraph: Seldom does the Boston Molasses Disaster of 1919 come up these days, but a recent spill that is wreaking havoc on the environment in Hawaii brought that long-ago tragedy back into the news.

abstract: Alan Berliner’s documentary “First Cousin Once Removed” follows Edwin Honig and his struggles with Alzheimer’s disease.
snippet: Alan Berliner’s documentary “First Cousin Once Removed” follows Edwin Honig and his struggles with Alzheimer’s disease.
lead_paragraph: Some years ago the documentarian Alan Berliner was going to make a movie about a California woman with superabundant autobiographical memory. “She remembered everything in her past,” Mr. Berliner said. “The neurologists studied her at UC Irvine for five years, and she was the real deal. No tricks. Extraordinary.”

headline.main: 56 Ways of Saying I Don’t Remember

abstract: Alan Berliner explores memory and forgetting in this short experimental documentary about his cousin Edwin Honig – a poet, translator and professor — and his journey through Alzheimer’s disease.
snippet: Alan Berliner explores memory and forgetting in this short experimental documentary about his cousin Edwin Honig – a poet, translator and professor — and his journey through Alzheimer’s disease.
lead_paragraph: This Op-Doc is part of a suite of short films collectively titled “Translating Edwin Honig: A Poet’s Alzheimer’s,” completed in 2010. The films form a portrait of the distinguished poet, translator, critic and Brown University professor Edwin Honig — who was my cousin, friend and mentor — and his journey through the depths of Alzheimer’s disease. It is the chronicle of a man who, though he may have lost his memory, his relationship to the past and his command of language, still retained his wit, his sense of humor, his scholarly demeanor and the bearings of a deeply poetic soul.

abstract: Professors at Johns Hopkins University plan to offer an online course in coping with dementia.
snippet: Professors at Johns Hopkins University plan to offer an online course in coping with dementia.
lead_paragraph: Recently, someone dear to me received the diagnosis of dementia, and I’ve been grappling with the frustrations of helping her adapt.
headline.main: Online Lessons in Dementia Management

abstract: My father told me that my grandmother lived not far from me in San Francisco. This was news: I’d last seen her almost 25 years before.
snippet: My father told me that my grandmother lived not far from me in San Francisco. This was news: I’d last seen her almost 25 years before.
lead_paragraph: My grandmother has Alzheimer’s disease. But in a lot of ways, she made us forget each other a long time ago.
headline.main: Forgetting Grandma
headline.print_headline: Forgetting Grandma

abstract: The federal agency overseeing Medicare is reluctant to endorse, or pay for brain scans to diagnose Alzheimer’s disease.
snippet: The federal agency overseeing Medicare is reluctant to endorse, or pay for brain scans to diagnose Alzheimer’s disease.
lead_paragraph: For all the hue and cry about detecting the earliest signs of Alzheimer’s disease, the federal Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services has concluded that amyloid brain scans for the purpose of diagnosing Alzheimer’s disease are not ready for prime time.
headline.main: Decision Casts Doubt on Brain Scans for Alzheimer’s

abstract: A daughter whose mother is 94 cares for the generations before and after her, living their lives and preserving their memories.
snippet: A daughter whose mother is 94 cares for the generations before and after her, living their lives and preserving their memories.
lead_paragraph: Reading was my mother’s escape from the Texas farm where she grew up. As a child, she memorized poems and recited them in her school auditorium. Later, she memorized whole books and performed them for women’s clubs. She stood alone onstage in high heels and a large hat while her voice transported her listeners to another world. You couldn’t take your eyes or ears off of her. Our home was a house of books, hundreds of which she knew by memory. Now she’s 94 and her once famous memory is slipping away.

abstract: HIgh blood glucose levels are tied to an increased risk of Alzheimer’s disease and vascular dementia in a new study.
snippet: HIgh blood glucose levels are tied to an increased risk of Alzheimer’s disease and vascular dementia in a new study.
lead_paragraph: People with diabetes face an increased risk of Alzheimer’s disease and other forms of dementia, a connection scientists and physicians have worried about for years. They still can’t explain it.
headline.main: High Blood Sugar Linked to Dementia

abstract: A spate of excellent movies about aging may reflect filmmakers’ dawning recognition of the way this global demographic shift affects all our lives.
snippet: A spate of excellent movies about aging may reflect filmmakers’ dawning recognition of the way this global demographic shift affects all our lives.
lead_paragraph: “She has her good days and her bad days, that’s all,” Craig Morrison, who is in his late 80s, testily tells his son. It’s an intensely self-sufficient man’s warning to back off, a we-don’t-need-anyone’s-help declaration that will sound familiar to many readers here.
headline.main: ‘Still Mine’ Adds to Movies on Aging

abstract: Twenty-one people were charged Tuesday after the Georgia Bureau of Investigation said it found widespread abuse of patients at a specialized care facility northeast of Atlanta.
snippet: Twenty-one people were charged Tuesday after the Georgia Bureau of Investigation said it found widespread abuse of patients at a specialized care facility northeast of Atlanta.
lead_paragraph: Twenty-one people were charged Tuesday after the Georgia Bureau of Investigation said it found widespread abuse of patients at a specialized care facility northeast of Atlanta. The bureau said its review had found that employees at Alzheimer’s Care of Commerce had struck patients, delayed changing diapers and used bedsheets as restraining devices. The inquiry also uncovered that people with felony convictions were involved in patient care, a violation of state regulations. The authorities filed more than 70 charges against current and former facility employees. The center’s owner, Donna Wright, was among those charged.
headline.main: Georgia: 21 Charged After Inquiry Finds Alzheimer’s Patients Were Abused
headline.print_headline: Georgia: 21 Charged After Inquiry Finds Alzheimer’s Patients Were Abused

abstract: A push for early detection and treatment, even in the absence of cognitive symptoms, of the amyloid plaques that indicate a risk for Alzheimer’s and other dementias has some researchers worried.

abstract: Baxter International said that the immunoglobulin therapy did not significantly arrest the decline in either cognition or daily functioning when compared with a placebo.
snippet: Baxter International said that the immunoglobulin therapy did not significantly arrest the decline in either cognition or daily functioning when compared with a placebo.
lead_paragraph: In yet another setback for the treatment of Alzheimer’s disease, Baxter International said Tuesday that its drug, Gammagard, had failed to halt the mental decline caused by the disease in a late-stage clinical trial.
headline.main: Alzheimer’s Treatment Failed Trial, Maker Says

abstract: A proposal to ease testing requirements is seductive but raises concerns about safety.
snippet: A proposal to ease testing requirements is seductive but raises concerns about safety.
lead_paragraph: The Food and Drug Administration has proposed lowering the bar for approving drugs to treat people at the earliest stages of Alzheimer’s disease, before they have developed any serious impairment or overt dementia. The goal is commendable — to find ways to prevent or slow the progression of this terrible disease before it can rob people of their mental capacities. But the proposal raises troubling questions as to whether the agency would end up approving drugs that provide little or no clinical benefit yet cause harmful side effects in people who take the medications for extended periods.
headline.main: Drugs for Early-Stage Alzheimer’s
headline.print_headline: Drugs for Early-Stage Alzheimer’s

abstract: Two new studies out of Europe have confirmed what researchers had long suspected: rates would fall and mental acuity improve as populations grew healthier and better educated.
snippet: Two new studies out of Europe have confirmed what researchers had long suspected: rates would fall and mental acuity improve as populations grew healthier and better educated.
lead_paragraph: A new study has found that dementia rates among people 65 and older in England and Wales have plummeted by 25 percent over the past two decades, to 6.2 percent from 8.3 percent, a trend that researchers say is probably occurring across developed countries and that could have major social and economic implications for families and societies.

abstract: Researchers found that older African-Americans with Alzheimer’s were slightly more likely to have one gene, ABCA7, that is thought to confer risk for the disease.
snippet: Researchers found that older African-Americans with Alzheimer’s were slightly more likely to have one gene, ABCA7, that is thought to confer risk for the disease.
lead_paragraph: African-Americans have a slightly higher risk of Alzheimer’s disease than people of largely European ancestry, but there is no major genetic difference that could account for the slight excess risk, new research shows.

abstract: Violent behavior often leads families to place people with dementia in care facilities.
snippet: Violent behavior often leads families to place people with dementia in care facilities.
lead_paragraph: For more than five years, Phyllis Edelstein managed to care for her husband Richard in their Long Island home as his dementia slowly progressed. She felt fortunate to have found, and to be able to pay for, a live-in couple to help her.
headline.main: When Aggression Follows Dementia

abstract: Two doctors, one now a patient, write about impending dementia and end-of-life care.
snippet: Two doctors, one now a patient, write about impending dementia and end-of-life care.
lead_paragraph: This week, let me pass along some of the more absorbing blogs and Web sites I’ve come across recently, other corners of the online world where people are talking about aging and caregiving from very different perspectives.
headline.main: Two Blogs Worth Reading

abstract: A reader laments that she did not have the chance to say goodbye before her husband’s death.

headline.print_headline: A Farewell to the Dying

abstract: People with Alzheimer’s disease or mild cognitive impairment may be more susceptible to emotional cues from those around them.
snippet: People with Alzheimer’s disease or mild cognitive impairment may be more susceptible to emotional cues from those around them.
lead_paragraph: Jean McFee Raichle, 94, is a remarkably cheerful woman. She lives in an assisted living center in Seattle staffed by aides who are warm and nurturing. She exists in the moment, mostly untroubled by her Alzheimer’s disease.
headline.main: Empathy Without Boundaries

abstract: Kate Hoit shares her letters of losing her father to Alzheimer’s disease while she was deployed to Iraq as a photojournalist.
snippet: Kate Hoit shares her letters of losing her father to Alzheimer’s disease while she was deployed to Iraq as a photojournalist.
lead_paragraph: “War does not determine who is right — only who is left.” That’s what Bertrand Russell said.
headline.main: Losing My Father at War, One Letter at a Time

abstract: A new study adds to evidence of a link between late-life depression and dementia.
snippet: A new study adds to evidence of a link between late-life depression and dementia.
lead_paragraph: A large body of research has linked late-life depression to social isolation, poorer health and an increased risk of death. Now, a new study finds that depression is associated with subsequent vascular dementia and Alzheimer’s disease, conditions poised to expand dramatically with the aging population.
headline.main: Does Depression Contribute to Dementia?

abstract: This spring, the Alzheimer’s Association plans to launch ‘social engagement’ groups nationwide for people with early-stage dementia.
snippet: This spring, the Alzheimer’s Association plans to launch ‘social engagement’ groups nationwide for people with early-stage dementia.
lead_paragraph: Three years ago, Kennard Lehmann walked out of a neurologist’s office in Sacramento, Calif., newly diagnosed with early-stage Alzheimer’s disease, a prescription in hand and absolutely no idea where to turn for help.
headline.main: After the Diagnosis, the Get-Togethers

abstract: Dementia doesn’t respect public stature or intellectual accomplishments.
snippet: Dementia doesn’t respect public stature or intellectual accomplishments.
lead_paragraph: The long list of roles Margaret Thatcher played during her 87 years — potent politician, free-market evangelist, labor antagonist, dominant global leader — includes the one she never publicly discussed: person with dementia.
headline.main: A Singular Life, an All Too Common End

abstract: The long-term consequences of U.S. budget cuts, in more than a few cases, are ominous. There is no better case study than Alzheimer's disease.
snippet: The long-term consequences of U.S. budget cuts, in more than a few cases, are ominous. There is no better case study than Alzheimer's disease.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Many Republicans, and Democrats, never thought the automatic across-the-board spending cuts known as sequestration would take effect. After all, they might produce dangerous, if unintended, consequences like potentially bankrupting the U.S. health care system, along with millions of families.
headline.main: Research Forgotten by Budget Cuts
headline.print_headline: Research Forgotten by Budget Cuts
byline.original: By Albert R. Hunt | Bloomberg View

abstract: Scientists investigating Alzheimer’s found that mice lacking the protein SNX27 had the same learning and memory defects as mice with Down syndrome.
snippet: Scientists investigating Alzheimer’s found that mice lacking the protein SNX27 had the same learning and memory defects as mice with Down syndrome.
lead_paragraph: The French geneticist Jérôme Lejeune discovered more than 50 years ago that Down syndrome is caused by the presence of an extra copy of chromosome 21. But to this day it has remained a mystery why that results in impaired physical and cognitive development. Now researchers at the Sanford-Burnham Medical Research Institute think they have found a clue.
headline.main: Protein Linked to Development Problems
headline.print_headline: Brain Chemistry: Protein Linked to Development Problems

abstract: Using a jarred brain as a teaching tool, my dad showed my 8-year-old self how brains with Alzheimer’s disease become smaller. But only after his death — and my mother’s confession about whose brain occupied that jar — did I figure out that my father was quite literally demonstrating how this disease runs through our heads.
snippet: Using a jarred brain as a teaching tool, my dad showed my 8-year-old self how brains with Alzheimer’s disease become smaller. But only after his death — and my mother’s confession about whose brain occupied that jar — did I figure out that my fath...
lead_paragraph: My gray matter might be waning. Then again, it might not be. But I swear that I can feel memories — as I’m making them — slide off a neuron and into a tangle of plaque. I steel myself for those moments to come when I won’t remember what just went into my head.

abstract: The bride is a research assistant in a Chicago Alzheimer’s center; the groom is a urology resident, also in Chicago.
snippet: The bride is a research assistant in a Chicago Alzheimer’s center; the groom is a urology resident, also in Chicago.
lead_paragraph: Cho Virginia Basden, the daughter of Jill Richards Basden and the Rev. Michael P. Basden of Naples, Fla., was married there Saturday to Dr. Daniel John Mazur, a son of Lillian Ekaczyk Mazur and Glen A. Mazur of New Lenox, Ill., at Trinity-by-the-Cove Episcopal Church, where the bride’s father is the rector. The Right Rev. Jeffrey D. Lee, the godfather of the bride and the bishop of the Episcopal diocese of Chicago, performed the ceremony with the Rev. Stephen Gerth, an Episcopal priest, assisting.

abstract: The number of people with dementia and the cost of caring for them are skyrocketing at a rate that rarely occurs with a chronic disease, a new study suggests.
snippet: The number of people with dementia and the cost of caring for them are skyrocketing at a rate that rarely occurs with a chronic disease, a new study suggests.
lead_paragraph: The most rigorous study to date of how much it costs to care for Americans with dementia found that the financial burden is at least as high as that of heart disease or cancer, and is probably higher. And both the costs and the number of people with dementia will more than double within 30 years, skyrocketing at a rate that rarely occurs with a chronic disease.

abstract: María Irene Fornés, who is suffering from Alzheimer’s disease, was welcomed by friends and fellow playwrights when relocated on Wednesday to a Manhattan nursing home.
snippet: María Irene Fornés, who is suffering from Alzheimer’s disease, was welcomed by friends and fellow playwrights when relocated on Wednesday to a Manhattan nursing home.
lead_paragraph: About a dozen friends and colleagues of the adventurous Cuban-born playwright and director María Irene Fornés gathered Wednesday morning near the Cathedral of St. John the Divine to await her arrival at Amsterdam House, the nursing home to which she was transferred from another facility in upstate New York. Just before 1 p.m. the small throng waved and applauded as Ms. Fornés, 82 and gaunt but seeming to enjoy the attention, was wheeled into the home.

abstract: When it came time for Sunny Harper-Owen to plan an event for her women’s group, she couldn’t do it. Then her female friends formed a new group — this one to support her.
snippet: When it came time for Sunny Harper-Owen to plan an event for her women’s group, she couldn’t do it. Then her female friends formed a new group — this one to support her.
lead_paragraph: The Supporting Sunny Group had planned this luncheon carefully. Because Sunny Harper-Owen, their longtime friend, warmly remembered the years she spent in Paris, the group had decided on a French theme and were bringing quiche, onion soup and chocolate mousse.
headline.main: For the Love of Sunny

abstract: The doctor, Joel Ross, is one of two physicians who prosecutors say leaked secret information about clinical drug trials that are at the center of the government’s insider-trading prosecution of the hedge fund SAC Capitol Advisors.
snippet: The doctor, Joel Ross, is one of two physicians who prosecutors say leaked secret information about clinical drug trials that are at the center of the government’s insider-trading prosecution of the hedge fund SAC Capitol Advisors.
lead_paragraph: A prominent New Jersey doctor specializing in Alzheimer’s disease has become ensnared in the government’s criminal case against a former portfolio manager at SAC Capital Advisors, the hedge fund owned by the billionaire investor Steven A. Cohen.

lead_paragraph: Michael French, whose long struggle with the brain disease frontotemporal dementia was the subject of a 2012 New York Times article and video, died Nov. 30 at a nursing home in Manhattan. He was 73.

lead_paragraph: This week’s Ask an Expert features Patty Cassidy, who will answer questions on how to use outdoor spaces and gardens to improve health and well-being, and what to do when the physical challenges of aging or mental challenges such as dementia and Alzheimer’s come into play.

abstract: The actress, accompanied by Katherine Cherbas on cello, sings “Me and My Mother” from Sara Cooper and Zach Redler’s musical.
snippet: The actress, accompanied by Katherine Cherbas on cello, sings “Me and My Mother” from Sara Cooper and Zach Redler’s musical.
lead_paragraph: In the musical “The Memory Show,” Leslie Kritzer plays a woman, identified simply as Daughter, who has moved home to take care of her aging mother, who is in the early stages of Alzheimer’s disease. In the song “Me and My Mother,” Daughter has just witnessed her mother’s first major episode of dementia. The show, with a book and lyrics by Sara Cooper and music by Zach Redler, continues through Saturday at the Duke on 42nd Street.
headline.main: In Performance: Leslie Kritzer of ‘The Memory Show’

abstract: On June 21 bridge players are being challenged to compete for at least part of approximately 16 hours from dawn to dusk to raise $100 an hour or more for the Alzheimer’s Association.
snippet: On June 21 bridge players are being challenged to compete for at least part of approximately 16 hours from dawn to dusk to raise $100 an hour or more for the Alzheimer’s Association.
lead_paragraph: Bridge marathons are few and far between. Four students played in London for 170 hours in 1969. Three years later four students in Edinburgh broke that record by 10 hours. The Young Chelsea Bridge Club in London has organized several marathons that last exactly 24 hours, but teams of three may enter.

abstract: In “First Cousin Once Removed,” Alan Berliner looks at Edwin Honig’s life as Alzheimer’s took its toll.
snippet: In “First Cousin Once Removed,” Alan Berliner looks at Edwin Honig’s life as Alzheimer’s took its toll.
lead_paragraph: “Recalling who I was, I see somebody else” begins a poem by Fernando Pessoa, quoted in Alan Berliner’s “First Cousin Once Removed.” In Mr. Berliner’s moving and mysterious documentary, the poet and translator Edwin Honig picks his way through his mind and memories in the falling shadow of Alzheimer’s. It’s the latest of Mr. Berliner’s dogged investigations into identity and family, and his strongest work yet, elevated by the presence of another artist in Mr. Honig, playfully insightful and eloquent even as his powers wane.

abstract: Even as an advocate for children with autism, I couldn’t keep my own son safe.
snippet: Even as an advocate for children with autism, I couldn’t keep my own son safe.
lead_paragraph: NOW in its sixth week, the search for Avonte Oquendo, a 14-year-old boy from Queens with autism, is shining a light on the issue of wandering among people with autism. On Oct. 4, Avonte managed to slip away after lunch from his school in Long Island City — even though he was known to wander during classroom transitions.

abstract: Ms. Segal’s new novel is set at a hospital where Alzheimer’s disease is spreading at a rapid rate.
snippet: Ms. Segal’s new novel is set at a hospital where Alzheimer’s disease is spreading at a rapid rate.
lead_paragraph: Lore Segal published her first novel in 1964. “Other People’s Houses” was a semi-autobiographical story about a young girl growing up in England after Hitler took control of Austria. When Ms. Segal was 10 years old, she left Vienna for England as part of the Kindertransport program. She moved to New York in 1951. In her new novel, “Half the Kingdom,” older hospital patients are mysteriously contracting Alzheimer’s disease at a rapid rate. In The New York Times Book Review, Patricia T. O’Conner wrote: “Fans of Segal’s fiction should feel right at home in this darkly comic novel.” In a recent e-mail interview, Ms. Segal, 85, discussed what the book says about aging, the recurring characters in her fiction, whether she ever thinks of retiring and more. Below are edited excerpts from the conversation:

abstract: Bobby Womack, 69, despite advancing age and what he said was Alzheimer’s disease, was in fine fettle on Friday at City Winery.
snippet: Bobby Womack, 69, despite advancing age and what he said was Alzheimer’s disease, was in fine fettle on Friday at City Winery.
lead_paragraph: Classic soul singing is, among countless other things, the art of the interjection. “Whoo!” “Mmmmm.” “Ohhhhhh.” “HahahaHA!” “Owww.” “Yeah, yeah!” “Am I lying?” Can I take my time?” “Listen to me!” “Do you feel it?” Used right, those interjections can be percussion, comedy, respiration, tension, release and more. Bobby Womack, 69, used them all at City Winery on Friday night, wearing a red leather suit, a red hat and red sunglasses as he started a three-night stand.

abstract: Records show that the chief executive of Star Scientific gave Kenneth T. Cuccinelli II, a candidate for governor and a former owner of stock in the company, thousands of dollars worth of gifts.
snippet: Records show that the chief executive of Star Scientific gave Kenneth T. Cuccinelli II, a candidate for governor and a former owner of stock in the company, thousands of dollars worth of gifts.
lead_paragraph: He first bought the tiny company’s stock after bunking down in its chief executive’s six-bedroom home.

abstract: Researchers thus far have to use tissue obtained posthumously to diagnose the degenerative brain disease that has bedeviled those who have sustained repeated hits to the head.
snippet: Researchers thus far have to use tissue obtained posthumously to diagnose the degenerative brain disease that has bedeviled those who have sustained repeated hits to the head.
lead_paragraph: For years, researchers have had to use tissue obtained posthumously to diagnose chronic traumatic encephalopathy, or C.T.E., the degenerative brain disease that has bedeviled athletes, soldiers and others who have sustained repeated head hits and concussions.

abstract: Saloua Raouda Choucair’s first exhibition in Beirut in 1947 is thought to be the first-ever show of abstract art in the Arab world. Now, as she copes with Alzheimer’s, her works are on display in London.
snippet: Saloua Raouda Choucair’s first exhibition in Beirut in 1947 is thought to be the first-ever show of abstract art in the Arab world. Now, as she copes with Alzheimer’s, her works are on display in London.
lead_paragraph: Saloua Raouda Choucair did everything in her life early, or late.

abstract: President Obama’s pledge of $100 million is a modest but welcome start to helping us understand how the brain works.
snippet: President Obama’s pledge of $100 million is a modest but welcome start to helping us understand how the brain works.
lead_paragraph: President Obama officially announced his new brain research initiative on Tuesday, with a pledge to put $100 million in his 2014 budget to support work at three federal agencies. It is a modest but welcome start for an effort that could transform our understanding of how the brain works and help researchers find new ways to treat and prevent brain disorders like epilepsy and Alzheimer’s.

abstract: Only players with the most severe brain injuries will be compensated, and the estates of retirees who died before 2006 would be excluded, according to a draft of the proposed settlement.
snippet: Only players with the most severe brain injuries will be compensated, and the estates of retirees who died before 2006 would be excluded, according to a draft of the proposed settlement.
lead_paragraph: When the N.F.L. agreed to pay $765 million to settle a lawsuit brought by 4,500 retired players who said the league hid from them the long-term impact of concussions, lawyers in the case said all retirees would be eligible for a share of the settlement.
headline.main: Many Ex-Players May Be Ineligible for Payment in N.F.L. Concussion Settlement
headline.print_headline: Many Ex-Players May Be Ineligible to Share in N.F.L. Concussion Deal

lead_paragraph: IF DNA is destiny, then Anne Wojcicki is in the right business.

abstract: After reports of technology companies cooperating with government surveillance efforts, Apple disclosed information about how it uses data from its online services.
snippet: After reports of technology companies cooperating with government surveillance efforts, Apple disclosed information about how it uses data from its online services.
lead_paragraph: Amid reports that technology companies cooperated with the United States government’s surveillance efforts, Apple has maintained that it does not provide the government with unfettered access to its servers. On Monday, the company released some numbers and information about its online services to try to prove it.

abstract: A college professor in Missouri recently ran a marathon while knitting a scarf over 12 feet long, weaving together pastimes first combined by an Englishwoman, Susie Hewer, in 2008.
snippet: A college professor in Missouri recently ran a marathon while knitting a scarf over 12 feet long, weaving together pastimes first combined by an Englishwoman, Susie Hewer, in 2008.
lead_paragraph: The long-distance friendship between Susie Hewer and David Babcock is held together by colored yarn and a world record few people knew existed.

abstract: Will it be helpful for health professionals using the new Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders — most of them not psychiatrists, but primary care doctors — to begin diagnosing mild neurocognitive disorder?
snippet: Will it be helpful for health professionals using the new Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders — most of them not psychiatrists, but primary care doctors — to begin diagnosing mild neurocognitive disorder?
lead_paragraph: The Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, published and periodically updated by the American Psychiatric Association, is one of those documents few laypeople ever read, but many of us are affected by.

abstract: Grid cells, which provide a sort of dead reckoning navigation, had until now only been recorded in some animals.
snippet: Grid cells, which provide a sort of dead reckoning navigation, had until now only been recorded in some animals.
lead_paragraph: Scientists’ discovery that rodents, bats and nonhuman primates have a system in the brain for what amounts to dead reckoning navigation is one of the most important brain research developments of the past few decades.
headline.main: Navigational Cells Located in Human Brains
headline.print_headline: Navigational Cells Located in Human Brains

abstract: The Virginia governor’s campaign contributor helped pay for his daughter’s wedding.
snippet: The Virginia governor’s campaign contributor helped pay for his daughter’s wedding.
lead_paragraph: A Washington Post article about the creepy relationship between Gov. Robert McDonnell of Virginia and Jonnie R. Williams, Sr., the head of a company called Star Scientific, offers an unusually good look at how money can buy political influence.
headline.main: A Political Marriage

abstract: That sense of reciprocity we often hear from caregivers — ‘she took care of me when I was young, so I need to help out now that she’s old’ — doesn’t seem to apply in late-life stepfamilies.
snippet: That sense of reciprocity we often hear from caregivers — ‘she took care of me when I was young, so I need to help out now that she’s old’ — doesn’t seem to apply in late-life stepfamilies.
lead_paragraph: Every year, Fran McDowell waited for the summer week when she would sing in a choral festival in the North Carolina mountains, then spend a few days in a lakeside cabin with close women friends.
headline.main: In Blended Families, Responsibility Blurs

abstract: Will robots be in every home, the way we now have TVs and computers? Will they work in our factories, fight in our wars, teach our children and care for our elderly?
snippet: Will robots be in every home, the way we now have TVs and computers? Will they work in our factories, fight in our wars, teach our children and care for our elderly?
lead_paragraph: Do you imagine a future where robots are ubiquitous, the way TVs and computers are now? Will robots work in our factories, fight in our wars, teach our children and care for our elderly? Or is that just science fiction?

abstract: One day after the announcement of a $765 million settlement in a concussion lawsuit, some former players and their families expressed mixed feelings.
snippet: One day after the announcement of a $765 million settlement in a concussion lawsuit, some former players and their families expressed mixed feelings.
lead_paragraph: Years ago, the symptoms started. Forrest Gregg would drag his left foot when he walked. He would thrash and kick and scream in the night, a nightmare running in his head. He would comb his hair with his right hand while his left hand trembled.

abstract: With a growing population of Americans over the age of 65, but a lack of trained home health care workers, more and more people could opt to hire robots to do the job.
snippet: With a growing population of Americans over the age of 65, but a lack of trained home health care workers, more and more people could opt to hire robots to do the job.
lead_paragraph: In the opening scene of the movie “Robot & Frank,” which takes place in the near future, Frank, an elderly man who lives alone, is arguing with his son about going to a medical center for Alzheimer’s treatment when the son interrupts him. “I brought you something,” he says to Frank. Then the son pulls a large, white humanoid robot from the trunk of his car.

abstract: Consumers should name an alternate contact to help make sure their long-term care insurance policies don’t mistakenly lapse.
snippet: Consumers should name an alternate contact to help make sure their long-term care insurance policies don’t mistakenly lapse.
lead_paragraph: Last week, my colleague Tara Siegel Bernard wrote about the challenges some consumers have had when trying to file claims for benefits under their long-term care insurance policies. One reader told about an experience she had when her mother – stricken with Alzheimer’s disease – canceled her own long-term care policy. Through persistent efforts, the reader said, she was able to have the policy reinstated, more than a year later.
headline.main: Preventing Lapses in Long-Term Care Policies
headline.print_headline:
Fixing Lapses
In Care Policies

abstract: “Struck by Lightning” kills its protagonist in the beginning of the film, then has him narrate the story from beyond the grave.
snippet: “Struck by Lightning” kills its protagonist in the beginning of the film, then has him narrate the story from beyond the grave.
lead_paragraph: It is usually not a smart idea to kill off a movie’s central character in its opening scene. But that’s what happens in “Struck by Lightning,” a rancid comic satire whose 17-year-old protagonist, Carson Phillips (Chris Colfer of “Glee”), is felled by a bolt from the blue in his high school parking lot.

abstract: A landmark study of the health and care of Medicaid patients provides some striking findings, but the longer-term conclusions that can be drawn are limited.
snippet: A landmark study of the health and care of Medicaid patients provides some striking findings, but the longer-term conclusions that can be drawn are limited.
lead_paragraph: The Oregon Health Study — one of the most important public-policy studies of the last decade — released a new round of results on Wednesday, showing that Medicaid coverage does not seem to make low-income adults much healthier, judging by biometric data. At least, that is one fair way to interpret the results, and it is basically the way the authors put it at the top of their new paper.
headline.main: What the Oregon Health Study Can’t Tell

abstract: The move for voluntary guidelines disappointed advocates for regulation of the product, which has been linked to the deaths of elderly patients.

lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Food and Drug Administration and the Consumer Product Safety Commission announced on Friday that they have called for a committee to update voluntary standards for adult portable bed rails, which have been linked to the deaths of hundreds of elderly patients.

abstract: In examining the ways stories keep us company during crises, Rebecca Solnit creates links between seemingly disparate ideas.
snippet: In examining the ways stories keep us company during crises, Rebecca Solnit creates links between seemingly disparate ideas.
lead_paragraph: Rebecca Solnit’s latest book, a series of essays loosely about story­telling, has a table of contents that sits on the page like a mountain tipped on its side. The essays’ titles mirror or refract one another, imparting symmetry. The summit, a chapter titled “Knot,” evokes another of the book’s metaphors, the bringing together of narrative threads. The tipped mountain shape resembles the traditional rise and fall of story structure. But this isn’t the only visual conceit. “Imagine all the sentences in this book as a single thread around the spool that is a book,” Solnit writes. You needn’t imagine it, though: One unspooled essay runs like a news ticker along the base of every page.

abstract: Anthony D. Marshall, 89, son of the philanthropist and socialite Brooke Astor, got a reprieve from prison as an appellate court considers his health.
snippet: Anthony D. Marshall, 89, son of the philanthropist and socialite Brooke Astor, got a reprieve from prison as an appellate court considers his health.
lead_paragraph: A last-ditch effort to keep Anthony D. Marshall, the 89-year-old son of the philanthropist and socialite Brooke Astor, out of prison succeeded on Thursday in buying him one more day as a free man.

abstract: The judge overseeing the proposed $765 million settlement in the N.F.L. concussion case appointed a special master to help analyze the final agreement, which could be filed in days.
snippet: The judge overseeing the proposed $765 million settlement in the N.F.L. concussion case appointed a special master to help analyze the final agreement, which could be filed in days.
lead_paragraph: The judge overseeing the proposed $765 million settlement between the N.F.L. and more than 6,000 players who sued the league for negligence and fraud has appointed a special master to help analyze the final agreement, which could be filed in days.
headline.main: In N.F.L. Case, Help in Analyzing Deal
headline.print_headline: In N.F.L. Case, Help in Analyzing Deal

abstract: Companies spend billions of dollars on drug testing each year. And yet for a surprising number of medicines, we still don’t know if they’re safe or effective.
snippet: Companies spend billions of dollars on drug testing each year. And yet for a surprising number of medicines, we still don’t know if they’re safe or effective.
lead_paragraph: EVERY spring, some 30,000 oncologists, medical researchers and marketers gather in an American city to showcase the latest advances in cancer treatment.

lead_paragraph: At the center of the government’s insider trading case against a former portfolio manager at the hedge fund SAC Capital Advisors is a trade that directly involves Steven A. Cohen, the billionaire owner of the fund.

abstract: The Obama administration is planning a decade-long scientific effort to examine the workings of the human brain and build a comprehensive map of its activity.
snippet: The Obama administration is planning a decade-long scientific effort to examine the workings of the human brain and build a comprehensive map of its activity.
lead_paragraph: The Obama administration is planning a decade-long scientific effort to examine the workings of the human brain and build a comprehensive map of its activity, seeking to do for the brain what the Human Genome Project did for genetics.

abstract: Edwin J. Torres, born and raised in the Bronx, moved from documenting urban life to focusing on intimate moments closer to home.
snippet: Edwin J. Torres, born and raised in the Bronx, moved from documenting urban life to focusing on intimate moments closer to home.
lead_paragraph: Edwin J. Torres, a 23-year-old photographer and filmmaker, is based in Manhattan but was born and raised in the Bronx. “I might move back,” he said. “I love it there.” He received a degree in American Studies from Colby College in Waterville, Me., but studied film and photography as well. He volunteers frequently at the Bronx Documentary Center and has been seleced to particpate in the Missouri Photo Workshop next month.
headline.main: Turning Back for the Missed Story

abstract: Adult children who have overseen their parents’ care say that besides physical and emotional strains, there are financial effects that can include a loss of job mobility.
snippet: Adult children who have overseen their parents’ care say that besides physical and emotional strains, there are financial effects that can include a loss of job mobility.
lead_paragraph: THROUGH the 1990s, Patrick Quirke’s career was sailing along. Every few years, he would be promoted at the transportation company where he worked and move to another city. He said he had every reason to believe that he would be promoted to the company’s headquarters in a few more moves. Then, his parents’ health started to decline.

abstract: Thousands, and possibly millions, of Medicare beneficiaries with chronic health problems can now continue to be covered for physical therapy because of an action by Congress and a recent court settlement.
snippet: Thousands, and possibly millions, of Medicare beneficiaries with chronic health problems can now continue to be covered for physical therapy because of an action by Congress and a recent court settlement.
lead_paragraph: Ellen Gorman, 72, a New York psychotherapist, can’t walk very far and gets around the city mainly by taxi, “which is really expensive,” she said. Twice since 2008 her physical therapy was discontinued because she wasn’t progressing. But after a knee replacement last year, she is getting physical therapy again, exercising with her therapist and building up her endurance by walking in the hallway of her Manhattan apartment building.
headline.main: Therapy Plateau No Longer Ends Coverage

abstract: The former N.F.L. linebacker Junior Seau had chronic traumatic encephalopathy when he committed suicide last spring, the National Institutes of Health said Thursday.
snippet: The former N.F.L. linebacker Junior Seau had chronic traumatic encephalopathy when he committed suicide last spring, the National Institutes of Health said Thursday.
lead_paragraph: The former N.F.L. linebacker Junior Seau had a degenerative brain disease linked to repeated head trauma when he committed suicide in the spring, the National Institutes of Health said Thursday.

abstract: A memoir by Pat Summitt, the University of Tennessee women’s basketball coach who helped revolutionize the game and won eight national titles.
snippet: A memoir by Pat Summitt, the University of Tennessee women’s basketball coach who helped revolutionize the game and won eight national titles.
lead_paragraph: College coaches have to construct teams — complex organisms — from players who are often just figuring out who they are, as athletes and as adults. They’re supposed to remember that the pieces they are fitting together, on the court or the field, are also students. And they have to rebuild again and again, with every graduation.

abstract: Recent developments in health and science news. This week: Researchers have found electric charges in water droplets that bounce off metal surfaces, and a secret to the longevity of naked mole rats.
snippet: Recent developments in health and science news. This week: Researchers have found electric charges in water droplets that bounce off metal surfaces, and a secret to the longevity of naked mole rats.
lead_paragraph: Thanks to the federal government shutdown, the big science news last week was a sudden halt to all manner of research projects. Scientists across the country found themselves locked out of their labs as any work deemed nonessential — a designation that could seem arbitrary at times — was stopped. “Academic medicine is no day at the beach,” said Ellen Beckjord, an assistant professor at the University of Pittsburgh Cancer Institute, to The Huffington Post. “It doesn’t help matters when the rug gets torn out from under you like this.”

abstract: Originally manufactured by Milton Bradley, Mr. Foley’s game was introduced in 1966 and has gone on to sell tens of millions of copies.
snippet: Originally manufactured by Milton Bradley, Mr. Foley’s game was introduced in 1966 and has gone on to sell tens of millions of copies.
lead_paragraph: Chuck Foley, a game designer who helped inaugurate a craze that rivaled the hula hoop, scandalized the puritanical and drove chiropractors wild with delight, died on July 1 in St. Louis Park, Minn. Mr. Foley, an inventor of Twister, was 82.

abstract: A lawyer for Anthony D. Marshall, 89, said he could not walk, clean himself or dress himself, and the Parole Board was set to interview Mr. Marshall after state officials determined he was eligible for medical parole.
snippet: A lawyer for Anthony D. Marshall, 89, said he could not walk, clean himself or dress himself, and the Parole Board was set to interview Mr. Marshall after state officials determined he was eligible for medical parole.
lead_paragraph: New York State corrections officials have determined that Anthony D. Marshall, the 89-year-old son of the philanthropist and socialite Brooke Astor, is so sick and frail that he is eligible to be released from prison after serving just one month on his sentence of one to three years.

abstract: Jessica Mindich is a jewelry designer who has begun transforming recycled pistols, rifles and shotguns from Newark into a line of sleek bangle bracelets.
snippet: Jessica Mindich is a jewelry designer who has begun transforming recycled pistols, rifles and shotguns from Newark into a line of sleek bangle bracelets.
lead_paragraph: Jessica Mindich is a jewelry designer who has begun transforming recycled pistols, rifles and shotguns from Newark into a line of sleek bangle bracelets. Twenty percent of the proceeds will go directly to the gun buyback program in Newark, she said.
headline.main: A Connecticut Mother Makes Bangles of Recycled Guns

abstract: Pat Summitt, the renowned women’s basketball coach who won eight national championships at the University of Tennessee, is now a No. 1 best-selling author, with the memoir “Sum It Up.”
snippet: Pat Summitt, the renowned women’s basketball coach who won eight national championships at the University of Tennessee, is now a No. 1 best-selling author, with the memoir “Sum It Up.”
lead_paragraph: A FISH CALLED GENO: Pat Summitt, the renowned women’s basketball coach from the University of Tennessee, is used to being No. 1: with 1,098 career victories, eight national championships and a win-loss ratio of .840, she is by some measures the most successful coach in N.C.A.A. history. So it makes a poetic kind of sense that her memoir — the wincingly titled “Sum It Up,” written with Sally Jenkins — would shoot straight to the top in its first week on the hardcover nonfiction list. The book is tumultuous and engaging (“one long roar of acceleration,” as Summitt describes her undefeated 1997-98 season), and unafraid to throw a good-natured elbow or two.

abstract: A decision by a midlevel appellate court upheld the top charge in the 2009 convictions of Anthony D. Marshall and a lawyer for Brooke Astor’s estate, making prison time more likely.
snippet: A decision by a midlevel appellate court upheld the top charge in the 2009 convictions of Anthony D. Marshall and a lawyer for Brooke Astor’s estate, making prison time more likely.
lead_paragraph: More than three years after they were convicted of looting the estate of Brooke Astor, her son and a lawyer for the estate lost a significant appeal on Tuesday, moving them much closer to being forced to serve their prison sentences.

abstract: Mr. Woosnam played professionally in Britain before becoming the commissioner of the North American Soccer League.
snippet: Mr. Woosnam played professionally in Britain before becoming the commissioner of the North American Soccer League.
lead_paragraph: Phil Woosnam, a Welsh professional soccer player who became the commissioner of the North American Soccer League in 1969 and held that post until 1983, helping to raise the sport’s profile in the United States, died on Friday in Marietta, Ga. He was 80.

abstract: Some family members of players involved in the concussion lawsuit were mostly positive about the outcome while the response from a few current and retired players was mixed.
snippet: Some family members of players involved in the concussion lawsuit were mostly positive about the outcome while the response from a few current and retired players was mixed.
lead_paragraph: When news circulated Thursday that the N.F.L. had agreed to pay $765 million to settle a concussion lawsuit, it was met with mostly positive reactions from some family members of players involved in the suit.

abstract: New companies are coming up with ways to make smartphones into devices to monitor the foot traffic in stores or keep track of Alzheimer’s patients with the kind of technology used in house arrests. With the right incentives, people might even choose to be watched.

lead_paragraph: Following people online, with cookies, tagged pixels and even voluntarily given information, has been a big business. Now much of the same technology is moving into the physical world.

abstract: If he had to do it all over again, parole board members asked Anthony D. Marshall, would he have done things differently? His reply: “Quite.”
snippet: If he had to do it all over again, parole board members asked Anthony D. Marshall, would he have done things differently? His reply: “Quite.”
lead_paragraph: After declining to speak at his trial or sentencing, Anthony D. Marshall was recently given one more chance to express remorse for stealing millions of dollars from his mother, the philanthropist and socialite Brooke Astor, in her waning years.

abstract: Higher rates of death from heart disease, cancer, homicide and diabetes help explain the 3.8-year gap in life expectancy between black and white Americans.
snippet: Higher rates of death from heart disease, cancer, homicide and diabetes help explain the 3.8-year gap in life expectancy between black and white Americans.
lead_paragraph: The gap in life expectancy between black and white Americans is at its narrowest since the federal government started systematically tracking it in the 1930s, but a difference of nearly four years remains, and federal researchers have detailed why in a new report.

abstract: Mr. O’Shea was an Irish actor known for his roles in films like “Ulysses,” “Barbarella” and “The Verdict” and plays like “Staircase” and “Mass Appeal.”
snippet: Mr. O’Shea was an Irish actor known for his roles in films like “Ulysses,” “Barbarella” and “The Verdict” and plays like “Staircase” and “Mass Appeal.”
lead_paragraph: Milo O’Shea, an Irish character actor — recognizable by his black bushy eyebrows, tumble of white hair and impish smile — whose films included “Ulysses,” “Barbarella” and “The Verdict,” died on Tuesday in Manhattan. He was 86.

abstract: May-Britt and Edvard I. Moser are exploring the way the brain records and remembers movement in space, which they speculate may be the basis of all memory.
snippet: May-Britt and Edvard I. Moser are exploring the way the brain records and remembers movement in space, which they speculate may be the basis of all memory.
lead_paragraph: TRONDHEIM, Norway — In 1988, two determined psychology students sat in the office of an internationally renowned neuroscientist in Oslo and explained to him why they had to study with him.

abstract: A healthy 28-year-old with concerns about diseases in her family had three different companies check her genetic code. The discrepancies in their results were striking.
snippet: A healthy 28-year-old with concerns about diseases in her family had three different companies check her genetic code. The discrepancies in their results were striking.
lead_paragraph: I like to plan ahead; that much I knew about myself before I plunged into exploring my genetic code. I’m a healthy 28-year-old woman, but some nasty diseases run in my family: coronary heart disease, rheumatoid arthritis, Alzheimer’s and breast cancer.

abstract: I wept for an awakening I had given up on, that around the corner I might love again.
snippet: I wept for an awakening I had given up on, that around the corner I might love again.
lead_paragraph: It’s important to understand that my husband, Peter, refuses to take baths. He does shower, yes, but he finds baths unmanly, just like soccer — or any other sport that does not require players to crash into one another like angry apes and beat their chests.

headline.main: A Warrior Learns a Different Pose

abstract: The National Institutes of Health has decided part of a grant from the N.F.L. to study brain injuries will go to two groups studying chronic traumatic encephalopathy, or C.T.E., in living patients.
snippet: The National Institutes of Health has decided part of a grant from the N.F.L. to study brain injuries will go to two groups studying chronic traumatic encephalopathy, or C.T.E., in living patients.
lead_paragraph: The National Institutes of Health outlined Monday how it planned to use part of a $30 million grant from the N.F.L. to finance a series of research projects designed to answer some of the most vexing questions about how and why athletes sustain traumatic brain injuries.

abstract: In Meghan Kennedy’s “Too Much, Too Much, Too Many,” a daughter tries to draw her mother out of her room, where she’s been bunkered since her husband died.
snippet: In Meghan Kennedy’s “Too Much, Too Much, Too Many,” a daughter tries to draw her mother out of her room, where she’s been bunkered since her husband died.
lead_paragraph: A grieving widow immures herself in her bedroom, surrounded by little more than stacks of overdue library books and her aching memory, in “Too Much, Too Much, Too Many,” a subdued but affecting new play by Meghan Kennedy that opened on Wednesday night at the Roundabout Underground’s Black Box Theater.

snippet: Ms. Handman was a behind-the-scenes force in Democratic politics, a theater preservationist and the first person to be awarded the National Medal of Arts for advocacy.
lead_paragraph: Bobbie Handman, a behind-the-scenes force in Democratic politics, a theater preservationist and the first person to be awarded the National Medal of Arts for advocacy, died on Thursday at her home in Manhattan. She was 85.

abstract: Television highlights.
snippet: Television highlights.
lead_paragraph: 8 P.M. (Discovery) UNDER SIEGE: AMERICA’S NORTHERN BORDER Reporters go under cover with the Homeland Security Department to patrol the border with Canada, focusing on an 863-mile stretch on either side of the Ambassador Bridge linking Detroit to Windsor, Ontario. The area has narrow crossings, heavy boat traffic and many landing spots, which make it especially difficult to stem the flow of illegal money, guns and drugs. The show also looks inside the Operational Integration Center, where live data of the entire border streams from an enormous wall of monitors.

abstract: The plea of not guilty by Mathew Martoma, a onetime SAC portfolio manager, sets the stage for a possible courtroom battle that would put the spotlight on the hedge fund and its owner, Steven A. Cohen.
snippet: The plea of not guilty by Mathew Martoma, a onetime SAC portfolio manager, sets the stage for a possible courtroom battle that would put the spotlight on the hedge fund and its owner, Steven A. Cohen.
lead_paragraph: The man at the center of the most lucrative insider trading case ever brought pleaded not guilty on Thursday, raising the stakes in the government’s investigation of his former employer, SAC Capital Advisors.

abstract: A former American Navy captain accused of involvement in the murders of two Americans after the 1973  coup may have been right under the noses of the investigators seeking his extradition.
snippet: A former American Navy captain accused of involvement in the murders of two Americans after the 1973  coup may have been right under the noses of the investigators seeking his extradition.
lead_paragraph: SANTIAGO, Chile — The Chilean courts have long been after Ray E. Davis, a former American Navy captain, accusing him of being involved in the murder of two Americans decades ago that inspired the award-winning 1982 film “Missing.”

abstract: Federal prosecutors have accused Mathew Martoma of making more than $276 million in a combination of illegal profits and avoided losses trading in the shares of the pharmaceutical companies Elan and Wyeth.
snippet: Federal prosecutors have accused Mathew Martoma of making more than $276 million in a combination of illegal profits and avoided losses trading in the shares of the pharmaceutical companies Elan and Wyeth.
lead_paragraph: Mathew Martoma, the former portfolio manager at SAC Capital Advisors, is set to stand trial on Nov. 4, almost a year after federal authorities charged him in what they called the largest insider trading case ever brought.

abstract: Eager to increase his name recognition, John A. Catsimatidis commissioned this highly biographical 60-second ad which will be shown on cable and broadcast television.
snippet: Eager to increase his name recognition, John A. Catsimatidis commissioned this highly biographical 60-second ad which will be shown on cable and broadcast television.
lead_paragraph: It is perhaps no surprise that the first mayoral candidate to begin running a costly television advertisement is the wealthy businessman John A. Catsimatidis, a Republican with a $3 billion fortune at his disposal. (His ad went up a few days before one for a Republican rival, Joseph J. Lhota, is to appear.) Eager to increase his name recognition and unhampered by spending limits because he is not participating in New York City’s voluntary public matching funds program, Mr. Catsimatidis commissioned this highly biographical 60-second ad, which will be shown on cable and broadcast television, from the Victory Group, which is based in Florida. The firm has worked with former Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani.
headline.main: The Ad Campaign: Catsimatidis Emphasizes Business Background
headline.print_headline: Citing Humble Origins, Catsimatidis Plays to His Strengths

abstract: Ms. Park’s best-selling books starred a sassy grade schooler with an imperfect grasp of English grammar who always found herself in some sort of predicament.
snippet: Ms. Park’s best-selling books starred a sassy grade schooler with an imperfect grasp of English grammar who always found herself in some sort of predicament.
lead_paragraph: Barbara Park, whose children’s books starring Junie B. Jones, a 6-year-old dispenser of abundant opinions, Runyonesque wisecracks and dubious syntax, have sold tens of millions of copies and delighted all but the most grammatically puritanical parents and teachers, died on Friday at her home in Scottsdale, Ariz. She was 66.

abstract: Television highlights.
snippet: Television highlights.
lead_paragraph: 10 P.M. (CBS) HOSTAGES Toni Collette stars as Dr. Ellen Sanders, whose husband (Tate Donovan) and children are taken captive by a rogue F.B.I. agent (Dylan McDermott, above with Ms. Collette), who then orders her to kill the president of the United States (James Naughton) during surgery. The show is “suspenseful and artfully layered,” Alessandra Stanley wrote in The New York Times, featuring lead characters who “are enemies with a special connection.” But, she added, “the premise that pits them against each other is almost impossible to prolong.” Once the mystery is solved, and the crisis is over, she said, “any prolongation turns into soap opera — and not the fun, campy kind on ‘Scandal’ or ‘Revenge.’ ”

A marathon of the final season’s episodes leads in, starting at 6 a.m. In “Graceland,” at 10, the season wraps as Jangles (Vincent Laresca), the sadistic Caza enforcer, takes a member of the house hostage.

abstract: Pope Benedict XVI may be stepping down, but don’t expect big changes in the Catholic Church.
snippet: Pope Benedict XVI may be stepping down, but don’t expect big changes in the Catholic Church.
lead_paragraph: To paraphrase Shakespeare, nothing became the papacy of Benedict XVI like his leaving it. I mean that as more than a backhanded tribute. How much suffering has mankind endured at the hands of leaders who could not bear to relinquish power, either because they feared the personal consequences of letting go or because they genuinely considered themselves indispensable? How rare are the big men who accept the verdict of time? In the Catholic Church they are once-in-six centuries rare. I have a soft spot for powerful people who know when to step down, and Benedict deserves respect for that.
headline.main: After Benedict: Don’t Get Your Hopes Up

snippet: Mr. Tolbert, a high school dropout, went on to play a central role in an early effort to improve the way that blacks were portrayed on film.
lead_paragraph: James L. Tolbert was in love. Marie Ross was too. But she had little interest in marrying a man who pieced together his income by hosting parties and concerts in empty buildings. One of his gimmicks: selling food and drink out of an old hearse.

abstract: Mr. Lemon was a civil rights activist whose objection to a 1968 Pennsylvania law gave rise to a watershed 1971 Supreme Court decision.
snippet: Mr. Lemon was a civil rights activist whose objection to a 1968 Pennsylvania law gave rise to a watershed 1971 Supreme Court decision.
lead_paragraph: Alton T. Lemon, a civil rights activist whose objection to state aid to religious schools gave rise to a watershed 1971 Supreme Court decision, died on May 4 in Jenkintown, Pa. He was 84.

abstract: Mr. Ansara had a busy career as a guest star on many of the best-known television series in the 1950s, ’60s and ’70s, everything from “Broken Arrow” to “Star Trek” to “I Dream of Jeannie” to “Kojak.”
snippet: Mr. Ansara had a busy career as a guest star on many of the best-known television series in the 1950s, ’60s and ’70s, everything from “Broken Arrow” to “Star Trek” to “I Dream of Jeannie” to “Kojak.”
lead_paragraph: Michael Ansara, a busy and widely recognizable character actor who was best known for portraying American Indians and later a Klingon in three different “Star Trek” series, died on Wednesday at his home in Calabasas, Calif. He was 91.

abstract: A dramatic photo of a procession for two children killed in Gaza City has been named 2012’s World Press Photo of the Year.
snippet: A dramatic photo of a procession for two children killed in Gaza City has been named 2012’s World Press Photo of the Year.
lead_paragraph: Paul Hansen’s dramatic image of a funeral procession in Gaza has been named 2012’s World Press Photo of the Year. The photo shows a group of men carrying the corpses of two children who were killed in Gaza City in November when their house was destroyed in an Israeli missile strike. Their father’s body is carried behind on a stretcher.

abstract: Television highlights.
snippet: Television highlights.
lead_paragraph: 8 P.M. (13) GREAT ZEBRA EXODUS In its final episode of the season, “Nature” travels to the Kalahari Desert in Botswana, where 20,000 zebras go in search of grass and water each year in a trek across the lunarlike landscape of the arid Makgadikgadi Pans. This documentary from the husband-and-wife filmmakers Adrian Bailey and Robyn Keene-Young views the journey through a single family: a stallion, its three mares and their offspring, which will walk more than 2,500 miles to feed themselves.

abstract: The University of California will lead a $9 million effort financed by the National Institute of Mental Health to identify promising drugs for autism and conduct early tests.
snippet: The University of California will lead a $9 million effort financed by the National Institute of Mental Health to identify promising drugs for autism and conduct early tests.
lead_paragraph: With the diagnosis of autism on the rise and drug companies facing major setbacks in developing successful treatments, the University of California, Los Angeles will lead a $9 million effort financed by the National Institute of Mental Health to find effective drugs, officials said Wednesday.

abstract: Television highlights.

lead_paragraph: 4 P.M. (TMC) SERENITY (2005) A small crew aboard a spaceship, led by Capt. Malcolm Reynolds (Nathan Fillion, left), tries to scrape together a living smuggling cargo from one fringe of the universe to the next in this film written and directed by Joss Whedon. But the crew members’ off-the-radar existence is threatened when an agent (Chiwetel Ejiofor) of an oppressive government tracks them down. Writing in The New York Times, Manohla Dargis compared this science-fiction adventure with the “Star Wars” movies by George Lucas. “Scene for scene, ‘Serenity’ is more engaging and certainly better written and acted than any of Mr. Lucas’s recent screen entertainments,” she wrote. “Mr. Whedon isn’t aiming to conquer the pop-culture universe with a branded mythology; he just wants us to hitch a ride to a galaxy far, far away and have a good time.”

abstract: Anthony D. Marshall, 89, has been deemed so frail and sick that he will be let out of prison after serving about 60 days of his sentence of one to three years.
snippet: Anthony D. Marshall, 89, has been deemed so frail and sick that he will be let out of prison after serving about 60 days of his sentence of one to three years.
lead_paragraph: New York State’s parole board ruled on Thursday that Anthony D. Marshall, the 89-year-old son of the philanthropist and socialite Brooke Astor, had grown so sick and frail that he would be granted immediate parole after serving just eight weeks of his one- to three-year prison sentence.

abstract: All of the documentaries in ESPN’s “Nine for IX” are devoted to women in the sports world, starting with the tennis star Venus Williams.
snippet: All of the documentaries in ESPN’s “Nine for IX” are devoted to women in the sports world, starting with the tennis star Venus Williams.
lead_paragraph: Title IX, the 1972 legislation banning sex discrimination in federally financed education, may have revolutionized women’s sports in America, but sports journalism hasn’t exactly kept up. Hence the existence of the new documentary series “Nine for IX,” beginning on Tuesday on ESPN.

abstract: Mr. LaMontaine, who won the Pulitzer Prize in 1959 and composed music for the Kennedy inauguration, had taken and passed a stockbrokers’ exam to support his career.
snippet: Mr. LaMontaine, who won the Pulitzer Prize in 1959 and composed music for the Kennedy inauguration, had taken and passed a stockbrokers’ exam to support his career.
lead_paragraph: John LaMontaine, a Pulitzer Prize-winning American composer whose works were performed widely and included the orchestral music for John F. Kennedy’s presidential inauguration, died on April 29 at his home in Hollywood, Calif. He was 93.

lead_paragraph: 10 P.M. (NBC) HANNIBAL The season ends as Hannibal (Mads Mikkelsen) turns on Will (Hugh Dancy, above right, with Mr. Mikkelsen) after Will arrives home without Abigail (Kacey Rohl). Jack (Laurence Fishburne) and the team find evidence that Will murdered her — and may actually be the Copy Cat Killer. Things get uglier as Will plots his escape and takes Hannibal back to Minnesota to clear his name.

abstract: Television highlights.
snippet: Television highlights.
lead_paragraph: 3 P.M. (TCM) CAMELOT (1967) Richard Harris stars as King Arthur; Vanessa Redgrave is Guenevere, his queen; and Franco Nero, above left with Harris and Ms. Redgrave, is Lancelot du Lac, her lover and her husband’s best knight, in this adaptation of the Lerner and Loewe musical, directed by Joshua Logan and written by Alan Jay Lerner. “It is hard to feel cozy with people you simply don’t understand,” Bosley Crowther wrote in The New York Times. “If we’re supposed to regard theirs as a clandestine ménage-à-trois, which is likely to be suspected from the campy way Mr. Harris sometimes performs, it isn’t developed sufficiently to make it daring or interesting.” Nonetheless, the film won Oscars for best art direction, best costume design and best music.

abstract: From 1971 to 1997, Zander Hollander edited compact yearbooks in which player profiles, statistics, rosters, records, schedules and previews could be found.
snippet: From 1971 to 1997, Zander Hollander edited compact yearbooks in which player profiles, statistics, rosters, records, schedules and previews could be found.
lead_paragraph: Zander Hollander sat silently on his couch. Rows of books — a large portion of them ones he created, edited and nurtured — hovered above him, dominating a wall in his Manhattan apartment.

abstract: Four young designers in London used their Design Museum residencies to investigate how humans relate to objects and technology.
snippet: Four young designers in London used their Design Museum residencies to investigate how humans relate to objects and technology.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — Identity can be difficult to pinpoint in the digital age, when it is easy to project multiple personalities online. So the four young designers in the residency program of the Design Museum in London explored how individuality can be expressed through technology — and how our attachment to material objects is changing.

abstract: Mr. Bucksbaum started General Growth Properties in 1954 with his brothers in small cities throughout the Midwest and expanded the company in concert with the growth of American suburbs.
snippet: Mr. Bucksbaum started General Growth Properties in 1954 with his brothers in small cities throughout the Midwest and expanded the company in concert with the growth of American suburbs.
lead_paragraph: Matthew Bucksbaum, who co-founded a family shopping mall empire that helped transform the landscape of suburbia and the habits of American consumers, died on Sunday at his home in Chicago. He was 87.

abstract: Scientists, researchers and some start-ups are preparing the next, even more intrusive wave of computing: ingestible computers and sensors in pills.
snippet: Scientists, researchers and some start-ups are preparing the next, even more intrusive wave of computing: ingestible computers and sensors in pills.
lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — They look like normal pills, oblong and a little smaller than a daily vitamin. But if your doctor writes a prescription for these pills in the not-too-distant future, you might hear a new twist on an old cliché: “Take two of these ingestible computers, and they will e-mail me in the morning.”

abstract: Dr. Ruddle, one of the first scientists to map genes’ locations on specific human chromosomes, helped lay the groundwork for the Human Genome Project.
snippet: Dr. Ruddle, one of the first scientists to map genes’ locations on specific human chromosomes, helped lay the groundwork for the Human Genome Project.
lead_paragraph: Francis Ruddle, a Yale University geneticist who plumbed the DNA of mice and men, and from whose laboratory sprang the first transgenic mammal — a mouse with added foreign DNA — died on March 10 in New Haven. He was 83.

abstract: In place of the Class Act, Congress has created a new Commission on Long-Term Care. Some doubt it will lead to anything.
snippet: In place of the Class Act, Congress has created a new Commission on Long-Term Care. Some doubt it will lead to anything.
lead_paragraph: The fate of the Class Act, which would have established the nation’s first voluntary public long-term care insurance program, was sealed in 2011 when the Obama administration shut it down, essentially calling it unworkable.

abstract: When Maria Mansfield conducts tours at Lincoln Center, it can get hilarious, risqué or weepy, depending on how she’s feeling the part that day.
snippet: When Maria Mansfield conducts tours at Lincoln Center, it can get hilarious, risqué or weepy, depending on how she’s feeling the part that day.
lead_paragraph: MARIA MANSFIELD’S TOURS of Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts are also tours of the life of Maria Mansfield. Expect some history and facts, sure. But the tours are really a one-woman show of Ms. Mansfield’s 45 years as a guide here, meeting and often befriending virtually every public figure associated with the place.

abstract: Anthony D. Marshall, who was convicted of stealing millions from Brooke Astor, was in court Friday to start serving his sentence after exhausting all appeals.
snippet: Anthony D. Marshall, who was convicted of stealing millions from Brooke Astor, was in court Friday to start serving his sentence after exhausting all appeals.
lead_paragraph: Anthony D. Marshall, the disgraced 89-year-old son of the Manhattan society doyenne Brooke Astor, finally surrendered on Friday to begin a prison sentence for stealing millions of dollars from his mother during her final years of life, ending a seven-year legal odyssey that came to define his own waning years.

abstract: Mr. Fisher created cartoons that managed to be erudite without being pretentious, requiring a general recognition of the world’s history and a healthy appreciation of irony.
snippet: Mr. Fisher created cartoons that managed to be erudite without being pretentious, requiring a general recognition of the world’s history and a healthy appreciation of irony.
lead_paragraph: Ed Fisher, whose culturally savvy cartoons, featured in The New Yorker for nearly 50 years, made wry sport of modern life, frequently matching images from history or folklore with captions in an up-to-date mode, died on April 3 in Canaan, Conn. He was 86.

abstract: Could I now learn who they really were?
snippet: Could I now learn who they really were?
lead_paragraph: My mother was abandoned in a French orphanage in Fez in 1941. That year in Morocco, hundreds of people died in an outbreak of the plague; her parents were among the victims. Actually, no, they died in a horrific car crash on the newly built road from Marrakesh to Fez. No, no, no, my grandmother died in childbirth, and my grandfather, mad with grief, gave the baby away. The truth is: I don’t know how my mother ended up in a French orphanage in 1941. The nuns in black habits never told.

abstract: Does history give us reason to be optimistic about 2014?
snippet: Does history give us reason to be optimistic about 2014?
lead_paragraph: War, famine, pestilence and death — the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse — have been well represented in years ending in “4,” but probably not disproportionately so. A look at memorable moments in the last seven of these just might lead to optimism for the one that’s upon us. Or not.

abstract: A militant fringe of one party in one house of Congress in one branch of government is trying to nullify an established law by extortion.
snippet: A militant fringe of one party in one house of Congress in one branch of government is trying to nullify an established law by extortion.
lead_paragraph: Sarah Palin finally got her death panels — a direct blow from the Republican House. In shutting down the government, leaving 800,000 people without a paycheck and draining the economy of $300 million a day, the Party of Madness also took away last-chance cancer trials for children at the National Institutes of Health.
